cell("markdown","# Math 03: Calculus — The Chain Rule\n\n**Learning Objectives:**\n1. Differentiate composite functions using the Chain Rule\n2. Decompose nested functions into layers for differentiation\n3. Implement chain-rule differentiation computationally\n\n**Prerequisites:** Math 02 (Derivatives & Power Rule)\n**Estimated time:** 90 minutes\n**Textbook:** *Justin Skycak — Calculus* §1.5"),
COLAB,
cell("markdown","---\n## Phase −1 — Theoretical Foundation\n\n### The Chain Rule\n\n> 📖 *From Calculus §1.5:* The chain rule tells us how to differentiate compositions of functions.\n> Informally: 'forget' about the inside, differentiate the outside, then multiply by the derivative of the inside.\n\nFor $y = f(g(x))$, let $u = g(x)$. Then:\n$$\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{dy}{du} \\cdot \\frac{du}{dx} = f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x)$$\n\n**Intuition:** Derivatives cancel like fractions: $\\frac{dy}{dx} = \\frac{dy}{du} \\cdot \\frac{du}{dx}$\n\n### Examples\n| $y$ | $u$ (inside) | $dy/du$ | $du/dx$ | $dy/dx$ |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| $(3x+1)^5$ | $u=3x+1$ | $5u^4$ | $3$ | $15(3x+1)^4$ |\n| $\\sqrt{x^2+1}$ | $u=x^2+1$ | $\\frac{1}{2\\sqrt{u}}$ | $2x$ | $\\frac{x}{\\sqrt{x^2+1}}$ |\n| $\\sin(x^3)$ | $u=x^3$ | $\\cos u$ | $3x^2$ | $3x^2\\cos(x^3)$ |"),
cell("code","# Symbolic verification\nimport sympy as sp\nx = sp.Symbol('x')\n\nexpressions = [(3*x+1)**5, sp.sqrt(x**2+1), sp.sin(x**3)]\nfor expr in expressions:\n    print(f'd/dx [{expr}] = {sp.diff(expr, x)}')"),
cell("markdown","### Multi-layer chains\n\nFor deeply nested functions, apply the chain rule repeatedly:\n$$\\frac{d}{dx}[f(g(h(x)))] = f'(g(h(x))) \\cdot g'(h(x)) \\cdot h'(x)$$\n\n**Example:** $y = \\sin^2(3x) = [\\sin(3x)]^2$\n- Layer 1: $u_1 = 3x \\Rightarrow du_1/dx = 3$\n- Layer 2: $u_2 = \\sin(u_1) \\Rightarrow du_2/du_1 = \\cos(u_1)$\n- Layer 3: $y = u_2^2 \\Rightarrow dy/du_2 = 2u_2$\n\n$$\\frac{dy}{dx} = 2\\sin(3x) \\cdot \\cos(3x) \\cdot 3 = 6\\sin(3x)\\cos(3x)$$\n\n> 💡 This layer-by-layer decomposition is **exactly how backpropagation works** in neural networks (Notebook 35-36)."),
cell("markdown","### Comprehension Check ✅\n1. Differentiate $f(x) = (2x^3-1)^4$\n2. Why can't you just use the power rule on $(2x^3-1)^4$ directly?\n\n<details><summary>💡 Answers</summary>\n\n1. $f'(x)=4(2x^3-1)^3 \\cdot 6x^2 = 24x^2(2x^3-1)^3$\n2. The power rule applies to $x^n$, not $(\\text{stuff})^n$. The chain rule accounts for the 'stuff' inside.\n</details>"),
